bout 1330","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Nanfan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French, Haitian, and Mauritian: nickname from French <i>fanfan</i> ‘baby, (little) child’. This surname is very rare in France. It was brought to the US mostly from Haiti, and also from the Dominican Republic, where it is of Haitian origin and rare."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Henry Nanfan was born about 1330, in Cornwall, England as the son of Sylvester Nanfan and Johanna De Penfons. He married Johanna Trethaek about 1360, in Cornwall, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. In 1374, at the age of 45, his occupation is listed as keeper of the fees in Cornwall, England. He died in 1374, at the age of 45."},"et":{"about 1330–1374":"umbes 1330–1374","1330–1374":"1330–1374","1334–Female":"1334–Surnud","1334–Male":"1334–Surnud","1361–Male":"1361–Surnud","1370–1460":"1370–1460","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","about 1360":"umbes 1360","ABT 1334":"umb